<Section collapsed="true" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 1" layout="Heading 1"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">Question 2.</Font></Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L117" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Write a Maple procedure <Font italic="true">LUFactorisation</Font> to implement the Doolittle method of finding a <Font bold="true">LU</Font> factorisation of a matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font>. Namely <Font italic="true">LUFactorisation</Font>(<Font bold="true">A</Font>) should take as input a square matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> and return a lower triangular matrix <Font bold="true">L</Font> with 1's on the diagonal and an upper triangular matrix <Font bold="true">U</Font>, such that <Font bold="true">A = LU</Font> (If such a factorisation exists).</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">LUFactorisation code</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L130" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">LUFactorisation := proc(A::Matrix);
local L, U, d, i, j, p, q, k;
L := copy(A);
U := copy(A);
d := RowDimension(A);
for k from 1 to d do
for i from k to d do
for j from k to d do
L[i,j] := U[i,j] / U[j,j]; L[i,i] := 1;
if j &gt; i then L[i,j] := 0; end if;
if i &gt; k then U[i,1..d] := U[i,1..d] - (U[i,k] / U[k,k])* U[k,1..d]; 
end if;
end do; 
end do;
end do;
return L, U;
end proc:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">How does it work?</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L172" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">First the LUFactorisation code makes a copy of the input matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> and saves it as both <Font bold="true">L</Font>, and <Font bold="true">U </Font>so that they can be altered later.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">It takes the Row Dimension of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> and saves it as d. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Next, in order for the matrix <Font bold="true">L </Font>to be adjusted into a lower triangular matrix then we need to change it's values as we perform row operations to the matrix <Font bold="true">U</Font> in order to make it upper triangular. Using 3 for loops, the code achieves this by firstly taking each value in the first row and updating them to be the equivalent value in the matrix <Font bold="true">U </Font>divided by it's diagonal. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Then it defines the diagonal of the matrix <Font bold="true">L </Font>to be 1 as that is what is required for the factorisation. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">For all j &gt; i, being the upper triangle of the matrix, the code defines the upper triangle of <Font bold="true">L</Font> to be equal to zero as required for the factorisation.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">For all i &gt; k, the upper triangle, the code performs row operations on the matrix <Font bold="true">U</Font>, reducing it to upper triangular form. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">The function returns the lower triangular matrix <Font bold="true">L</Font> and the upper triangular matrix <Font bold="true">U</Font> and terminates.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
