<Section collapsed="true" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 1" layout="Heading 1"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">Question 3.</Font></Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L128" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Use the procedures <Font italic="true">LUFactorisation</Font>,<Font italic="true"> BackSub</Font> and <Font italic="true">ForwardSub</Font> to implement a linear system solver <Font italic="true">LUSolve </Font>which takes as input a matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> that has an <Font bold="true">LU</Font> factorisation, and a vector <Font bold="true">y</Font>, and returns the solution to the linear system <Font bold="true">Ax = y</Font> or an error message if <Font bold="true">A</Font> is not invertible or <Font bold="true">A</Font> and <Font bold="true">y</Font> don't have the right dimensions.</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">LUSolve</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L131" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">LUSolve := proc(A::Matrix,y::Vector)::Vector;
local S, L, U, RA, CA, RY, CY;
S := copy(A);
RA := RowDimension(A);
CA := ColumnDimension(A);
RY := RowDimension(y);
CY := ColumnDimension(y);
L,U := LUFactorisation(S);
if RA &lt;&gt; CA then return (&quot;Error: Input Matrix must be square. I.e. #Rows = #Columns&quot;);
elif CY &lt;&gt; 1 then return (&quot;Error: Input Vector has incorrect dimensions. Must be a column vector.&quot;);
elif RY &lt;&gt; RA then return (&quot;Error: Input Matrix and Vector must be of equal dimension. I.e. The number of Rows/Columns in the Matrix must be equal to the number of rows in the Vector.&quot;);
elif Determinant(A) = 0 then return(&quot;Error: Input Matrix is singular (Non-invertible)&quot;);
else S := BackSub(U, ForwardSub(L, y));
end if;
return S;
end proc:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">How does it work?</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L174" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">First the LUSolve code saves the Row Dimension and Column Dimension of both the input matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> and vector <Font bold="true">y</Font>. In order to not change the definition of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> while running this code, we have also defined a new matrix <Font bold="true">S</Font>, which is a copy of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font>, which will be returned instead. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">The code then defines new matrices <Font bold="true">L</Font> and <Font bold="true">U</Font> which are the lower and upper factorisation of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font>. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">If the Row Dimension of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> is not equal to the Column Dimension, the code returns the error message &quot;Error: Input Matrix must be square. I.e. #Rows = #Columns&quot; and terminates.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Else, if the the Column Dimension of <Font bold="true">y</Font> is not 1, i.e. <Font bold="true">y </Font>is a matrix and not a vector, the code returns the error message &quot;Error: Input vector has incorrect dimensions. Must be a column vector.&quot; and terminates.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Else, if the Row Dimension of <Font bold="true">A</Font> is not equal to the Row Dimension of <Font bold="true">y</Font>, then the code returns the error message &quot;Error: Input Matrix and Vector must be of equal dimension. I.e. The number of rows/columns in the matrix must be equal to the number of rows in the vector.&quot; and terminates.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Else, if the determinant of <Font bold="true">A</Font> is equal to 0, the code returns the error message &quot;Error: Input Matrix is singular (non- invertible)&quot; and terminates.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Else, the code redefines the new matrix <Font bold="true">S</Font> to be the Back substitution of the matrix <Font bold="true">U</Font> with the solution to the forward substitution of the matrix <Font bold="true">L</Font> with the vector <Font bold="true">y</Font>. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">The code returns <Font bold="true">S</Font> and terminates.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
