<Section collapsed="true" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 1" layout="Heading 1"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">Question 4.</Font></Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L140" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true">Write a Maple procedure <Font italic="true">ColOperation</Font> to perform the following column operation:
<Font italic="true">ColOperation</Font>(<Font bold="true">M,p,q,x</Font>) should take as input any matrix <Font bold="true">M</Font> (of arbitrary size m by n) and return the result of subtracting <Font bold="true">x</Font> times the qth column from the <Font bold="true">p</Font>th column if <Font bold="true">p</Font> is not equal to <Font bold="true">q</Font>. However, if <Font bold="true">p</Font> is equal to <Font bold="true">q</Font> then it should return the result of multiplying the <Font bold="true">p</Font>th row by <Font bold="true">1/x</Font>. 

You may want to modify your procedure <Font italic="true">RowOperation2</Font> from the first practical.</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">ColOperation code</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L141" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">ColOperation := proc(A::Matrix, p, q, x)::Matrix;
local CA,Cp,Cq,B;
CA := ColumnDimension(A);
B := copy(A);
if (p &lt;= 0 or q &lt;= 0) then return (&quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that are positive and non-zero&quot;);
elif (p &gt; CA or q &gt; CA) then return (&quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that do not exceed the Column dimensions of the matrix.&quot;);
elif p = q then Cp := B[..,p]; B[..,p] := Cp/x;
else Cp := B[..,p]; Cq := B[..,q]; B[..,p] := Cp - x*Cq;
end if;
return B;
end proc:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">How does it work?</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L176" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">The ColOperation code first defines the Column Dimension of the input matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> and saves it as CA.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Next the code makes a copy of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> and saves it as the matrix <Font bold="true">B</Font> so that the definition of <Font bold="true">A </Font>is not altered when applying the code.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">If the input variables <Font bold="true">p</Font> or <Font bold="true">q</Font> are less than or equal to 0, the code returns the error message &quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that are positive and non-zero&quot; and terminates.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Else, if the variables <Font bold="true">p</Font> or <Font bold="true">q</Font> exceed the Column Dimension of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font>, the code returns the error message &quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that do not exceed the Column dimensions of the matrix.&quot; and terminates.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Else, if <Font bold="true">p = q</Font>, then the code defines Cp to be the pth column, then redefines the pth column to be Cp/x where x is a variable input and then returns the matrix <Font bold="true">B </Font>and terminates.
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Else, the code defines CP to be the pth column and Cq to be the qth column, then redefines the pth column to be the difference of Cp and x times Cq. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">The code then returns the matrix <Font bold="true">B</Font> and terminates.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">Testing code</Text-field></Title>
