<Section collapsed="true" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 1" layout="Heading 1"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">Question 5.</Font></Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L149" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true">Write a Maple procedure GSProcess that will take as input any matrix <Font bold="true">M</Font> (of arbitrary size m by n) and return the matrix <Font bold="true">Q </Font>which is the result of performing Gram-Schmidt process on the columns of <Font bold="true">M</Font>, starting from the left most column.</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">GSProcess code</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L150" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">GSProcess := proc(M::Matrix)::Matrix;
local Q, i, j, projection;
Q := copy(M);
for i from 1 to ColumnDimension(M) do
for j from 1 to i-1 do
projection := (Q[..,i] . Q[..,j])/(Q[..,j] . Q[..,j]); 
Q[..,i] := Q[..,i] - projection*Q[..,j];
end do;
Q[..,i] := Q[..,i]/sqrt(Q[..,i] . Q[..,i]);
end do;
return Q;
end proc:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">How does this work?</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L180" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Firstly, the GSProcess code makes a copy of the input matrix <Font bold="true">M</Font> and saves it as <Font bold="true">Q</Font> in order to not change the definition of <Font bold="true">M</Font> through the application of the code. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Then the code considers each column individually, for j from 1 to i-1, meaning it only applies to i &gt; 2, it defines the projection to be the inner product of a row and it's preceeding row over the inner product of the preceeding row with itself. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Within a for loop, the code takes the ith column and redefines it to be the difference between the ith column and the projection of the ith column with respect to the jth column. For i greater than 2, the code then sums up the projections. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">After the for loops end, the code then redefines each column to be the normalised vector of that column. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">The code then returns the adjusted matrix <Font bold="true">Q</Font> and terminates.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
