<Section collapsed="true" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 1" layout="Heading 1"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">Question 6.</Font></Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L156" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" bold="true">
</Font><Font opaque="true">Modify your procedure <Font italic="true">GSProcess</Font> to implement a new procedure <Font italic="true">QRFactorisation</Font> that will take as input any matrix <Font bold="true">M</Font> (of arbitrary size m by n) and return the matrix <Font bold="true">Q</Font> and also the corresponding upper triangular matrix <Font bold="true">R</Font>.</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">QRFactorisation code</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L157" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">QRFactorisation := proc(M::Matrix);
local Q, R, i, j, projection;
R := Matrix(ColumnDimension(M));
Q := GSProcess(M);
for i from 1 to ColumnDimension(M) do
for j from 1 to ColumnDimension(M) do
R[i,j] := (Q[..,i] . M[..,j]);
end do;
end do;
return Q,R;
end proc:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
<Section collapsed="false" isCollapsible="true" drawButton="true" MultipleChoiceAnswerIndex="-1" MultipleChoiceRandomizeChoices="false" TrueFalseAnswerIndex="-1" EssayAnswerRows="5" EssayAnswerColumns="60"><Title><Text-field style="Heading 2" layout="Heading 2">How does it work?</Text-field></Title>
<Group labelreference="L182" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Firstly, the QRFactorisation code defines a matrix <Font bold="true">R</Font> to be some matrix of equal dimensions to the input matrix <Font bold="true">M</Font>, it does this to avoid changing the definition of <Font bold="true">M</Font>, through the application of the code. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">The code then defines <Font bold="true">Q</Font> to be the matrix <Font bold="true">M</Font> after having applied the Gram-Schmidt process. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Then, the code defines a new matrix <Font bold="true">R</Font>, where each element determined by position (i, j) is defined as the dot product of the ith column of <Font bold="true">Q</Font> and the jth column of <Font bold="true">M</Font>. 
</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Then, the code returns the matrix <Font bold="true">Q</Font> alongside the new matrix <Font bold="true">R</Font>, and terminates. </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
</Section>
